In summary, the use of strategies involving γδ T cells in the context of malaria is a promising but challenging field of research because of the complexities of malaria infection. Moreover, most immunotherapy interventions are costly, especially those designed for cancer, and malaria is a widespread infectious disease in low- or middle-income countries. Nevertheless, several approaches should be pursued for the use of γδ T cells in malaria (
Figure 1
).
